HISTOGRAMS
print("\n========== HISTOGRAMS ==========")
Explanation
Prints heading.

df.hist(figsize=(10,8))
Explanation
Creates histogram for all numeric columns.
Histogram Meaning
A histogram shows:
frequency of values
distribution of data
Example
For sepal_length
x-axis → sepal length values
y-axis → number of flowers
figsize=(10,8)
Graph size:
width = 10
height = 8

plt.suptitle("Histograms of Iris Features")
Explanation
Adds main title to all histograms.

Output Title
Histograms of Iris Features
plt.show()
Explanation
Displays histogram graph.

Without this line graph may not appear.

BOXPLOTS
print("\n========== BOXPLOTS ==========")
Explanation
Prints heading.

features = df.columns[:-1]
Explanation
df.columns gives all column names.
Output
['sepal_length','sepal_width',
 'petal_length','petal_width','species']
[:-1] means: take all columns except last one.
Why?
Because species is text data and boxplot works mainly on numeric data.

Result
features =
['sepal_length','sepal_width',
 'petal_length','petal_width']
for col in features:
Explanation
Loop runs one by one for every feature.
Example
First:
col = sepal_length
Then:
col = sepal_width
and so on.

plt.figure()
Explanation
Creates new graph window for every boxplot.

Without this all boxplots may overlap.
sns.boxplot(x="species", y=col, data=df)

Explanation
Creates boxplot.
Meaning
x="species"
species shown on x-axis
y=col
selected feature on y-axis
data=df
dataset used
Example
If:
col = "petal_length"
Then graph becomes:
x-axis → setosa, versicolor, virginica
y-axis → petal length

What Boxplot Shows
A boxplot shows:
Minimum
Q1
Median
Q3
Maximum
Outliers

Important Parts
Part	Meaning
Middle line	Median
Box lower	Q1
Box upper	Q3
Dots outside	Outliers
plt.title(f"Boxplot of {col}")
Explanation
Adds title dynamically.

Example
If col = petal_width

Output title:
Boxplot of petal_width
plt.show()
Explanation
Displays boxplot graph.

OBSERVATIONS
print("\n========== OBSERVATIONS ==========")
Explanation
Prints heading.

print("1. Sepal features show overlap between species.")
Meaning
Different flower species have similar sepal values.

Hard to separate species using sepal only.

print("2. Petal features clearly separate species.")
Meaning
Petal length and width differ clearly.

Easy to identify species.

Example:

Setosa has very small petals.

Virginica has large petals.

print("3. Some outliers are present in sepal_width.")
Meaning
Some values are unusually high or low.

These appear as dots in boxplot.

print("4. Petal length and width are most important features.")
Meaning
These features help most in classification.

